{{ pc.standardSection('id="why"') }}
    <h3 id="why-this-matters">Why This Matters</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Layout Integrity:</strong> No wrapper elements breaking CSS Grid, Flexbox, or table structures.</li>
        <li><strong>Clean Authoring:</strong> Simple directives use <code>&lt;template is=""&gt;</code>—no boilerplate comments.</li>
        <li><strong>Debuggable Runtime:</strong> Comment markers persist for inspection, even when templates are gone.</li>
        <li><strong>Runtime Flexibility:</strong> Works with server-rendered HTML, no build step required.</li>
        <li><strong>Progressive Enhancement:</strong> Enhance existing markup rather than replacing it.</li>
        <li><strong>Familiar Patterns:</strong> Lifecycle callbacks mirror Custom Elements, reducing learning curve.</li>
    </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="ssr"') }}
    <h3 id="ssr-contract">SSR Contract</h3>
    <p>
        This section defines the server-side rendering contract for <strong>Web Directives</strong>.
        The server MUST expand all structural directives into their final HTML form.
        <code>&lt;template is="..."&gt;</code> elements and comment directive source markup MUST NOT appear in server output —
        only the expanded content with optional comment boundary markers.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-server-output">Server Output Requirements</h4>
    <div class="comparison-table-wrapper mt-4">
        <we-data-table><table class="comparison-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Directive</th>
                    <th>Server Output HTML</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>for-each</strong></td>
                    <td>
<we-code-view><pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;!-- control:for-each items="users" key="id" --&gt;
&lt;div class="user-row" data-key="1"&gt;Alice&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="user-row" data-key="2"&gt;Bob&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;!-- /control:for-each --&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>
                    </td>
                    <td>All items expanded. Comment boundaries SHOULD be included for client diffing. Keyed items MUST include <code>data-key</code> attribute.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>if</strong></td>
                    <td>
<we-code-view><pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;!-- control:if condition="isAdmin" --&gt;
&lt;button class="admin-action"&gt;Delete&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;!-- /control:if --&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST evaluate the condition. Only the matching branch is emitted. If false, emit empty markers only.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>switch / case</strong></td>
                    <td>
<we-code-view><pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;!-- control:switch value="status" --&gt;
&lt;span class="badge success"&gt;Active&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;!-- /control:switch --&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST evaluate the active case and emit only that branch.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>resource:loader</strong></td>
                    <td>
<we-code-view><pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;!-- resource:loader name="user-profile" --&gt;
&lt;user-card&gt;...resolved data...&lt;/user-card&gt;
&lt;!-- /resource:loader --&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST evaluate the data state and emit the corresponding template (success, empty, or error). For streaming SSR, loading template MAY be emitted first.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>defer</strong></td>
                    <td>
<we-code-view><pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;!-- defer on="visible" --&gt;
&lt;div class="skeleton"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;!-- /defer --&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server emits the <strong>placeholder</strong> branch (the pre-trigger state) plus boundary markers; the <strong>content</strong> branch is deferred and stamped client-side when the trigger fires. Supersedes the earlier <code>lazy</code> proposal.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table></we-data-table>
    </div>

    <h4 id="ssr-wire-format">Wire Format (normative — byte-exact)</h4>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        The externally-observable SSR output is a <strong>language-agnostic wire format</strong>: a renderer in
        any language (Node, Go, Rust, PHP, …) is conformant iff it emits these exact bytes, so the single JS
        client hydrates every server's output identically (per
        <a href="/backlog/2030-foundational-ssr-hydration-surface-for-comment-anchor-direct/">#2030</a>).
        The wire format — not the render code — is the swap boundary.
    </p>
    <ol class="list-decimal ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li>
            <strong>Open/close marker grammar (space-padding is normative).</strong> A directive region is
            delimited by a paired open and close comment. The open marker is
            <code>&lt;!-- <var>namespace</var>:<var>name</var><var> options</var> --&gt;</code>; the close marker
            is <code>&lt;!-- /<var>namespace</var>:<var>name</var> --&gt;</code>. There is <strong>exactly one
            ASCII space</strong> immediately after the opening <code>&lt;!--</code> and <strong>exactly one ASCII
            space</strong> immediately before the closing <code>--&gt;</code> of every marker. The close marker's
            token begins with a single <code>/</code> and carries the namespace-qualified name only (never the
            options). Renderers MUST NOT emit tabs, newlines, or additional spaces inside single-line markers, so
            the delimiter is a stable byte sequence the client can string-match.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong><code>data-key</code> keyed diffing.</strong> Every item element emitted by a keyed
            <code>for-each</code> MUST carry a <code>data-key="<var>key</var>"</code> attribute whose value is the
            item's key projected to a string. The client reads <code>data-key</code> for keyed reconciliation; it
            is the only key channel (keys are never serialized into comment text — see the state token below).
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Zero-JS progressive baseline.</strong> All structural content between the markers is fully
            expanded in the emitted bytes (lists enumerated, the live <code>if</code>/<code>switch</code> branch
            present, resolved resource data inline). The document is complete and readable with no JavaScript;
            markers are inert comments.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>State-token layout (bounded, in the open marker).</strong> A directive that needs resume state
            for hydration serializes it as <strong>bounded framework tokens inside its open marker's option
            list</strong> (e.g. <code>value="…"</code> on <code>switch</code>, <code>condition="…"</code> on
            <code>if</code>). Two constraints are normative for every language: (a) per-item keys travel on
            <code>data-key</code>, never in comment text; (b) renderers MUST NOT serialize raw user data into
            comment text — HTML comments cannot contain <code>--</code> or <code>--&gt;</code>, so doing so risks
            parser breakout/injection. Large or shared state is a future, measured
            <code>&lt;script type="application/json"&gt;</code> side-channel — and if adopted becomes a
            <em>standard</em> addition, not a per-renderer one.
        </li>
    </ol>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-2">
        <strong>Conformance vectors.</strong> This wire format is pinned by a WE-owned, language-agnostic vector
        set — <code>(input directive tree + data) → exact expected HTML bytes</code> — that every renderer passes
        (the <a href="/backlog/817-constellation-placement-of-guard-validity-merge-validator-re/">#817</a>/<a href="/backlog/899-behavioral-conformance-vectors-in-browser-implementer-valida/">#899</a>
        protocol-plus-vectors, data-not-impl pattern). The vectors live at
        <code>we:conformance-vectors/webdirectives-ssr.vectors.ts</code>; WE ships the vectors + the structural
        schema validator, never a renderer. The published grammar is <code>control:</code>/<code>/control:</code>
        <code>open-close</code> — the FUI runtime's legacy <code>:start</code>/<code>:end</code> spelling is a
        pre-existing conformance gap reconciled to this standard separately
        (<a href="/backlog/2068-reconcile-fui-runtime-directive-markers-to-the-standard-open/">#2068</a>).
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-hydration-expectations">Client Hydration Expectations</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Comment boundaries:</strong> Client uses <code>&lt;!-- control:... --&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;!-- /control:... --&gt;</code> as delimiters to identify directive-managed DOM regions.</li>
        <li><strong>Keyed diffing:</strong> For <code>for-each</code> directives, the client reads <code>data-key</code> attributes to perform efficient keyed reconciliation when data changes.</li>
        <li><strong>Template absence:</strong> Client MUST NOT expect <code>&lt;template is="..."&gt;</code> elements in the DOM — these are authoring artifacts replaced by the server.</li>
        <li><strong>Directive re-attachment:</strong> Client attaches directive logic (event listeners, mutation tracking) to the comment boundary markers and their enclosed content.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 id="ssr-progressive-baseline">Progressive Enhancement Baseline</h4>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        With zero JavaScript, all structural content is fully rendered: lists are expanded, conditionals are evaluated,
        resource loaders show resolved data. The page is complete and readable.
        Comment markers are invisible to users. No interactivity — content is static.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-client-only">Client-Only Features</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Dynamic re-evaluation:</strong> Updating <code>for-each</code> items, toggling <code>if</code> conditions, or switching <code>switch</code> values</li>
        <li><strong>Template instantiation:</strong> <code>&lt;template is="..."&gt;</code> directive registration and runtime cloning</li>
        <li><strong>Lazy directive:</strong> Deferred content loading triggered by viewport or interaction</li>
        <li><strong>Comment parser registration:</strong> <code>customComments.define()</code> and custom parser plugins</li>
        <li><strong>Directive lifecycle callbacks:</strong> <code>connectedCallback</code>, <code>disconnectedCallback</code>, <code>optionsChangedCallback</code></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h4 id="ssr-implementor-note" style="margin-top: 0; color: #d97706; font-size: 1rem;">Implementor Note</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
            This contract defines compliance requirements. The build system or server framework
            is responsible for expanding directives and emitting comment boundary markers.
            Web Directives does not ship an SSR runtime — it ships this specification.
            See also: <a href="/projects/webexpressions/#ssr">Web Expressions SSR</a> for expression resolution within directive content.
        </p>
    </div>
